(2)National Health Insurance Corporation, Seoul, Korea.
(3)Institute of Health Services Research, Yonsei University, Seoul, Korea 
Department of Preventive Medicine, Yonsei University College of Medicine, Seoul, 
Korea.
(4)Division of Business Administration, Yonsei University, Seoul, Korea.
(5)Institute of Health Services Research, Yonsei University, Seoul, Korea 
Department of Preventive Medicine, Yonsei University College of Medicine, Seoul, 
Korea mann@yuhs.ac.

This study investigates the relationship between economic status and mortality 
of Korean men and women who were under and over the average national life 
expectancy using Cox's proportional hazard model to adjust for health status, 
past medical history, and age. The study subjects come from local applicants of 
Korean National Health Insurance who had a health examination in 2005. They were 
enrolled into a follow-up investigation from 2005 to 2011. In individuals 
younger than the average life expectancy, the mortality of the lowest economic 
status was 2.48 times higher in men and 2.02 times higher in women than that in 
the highest economic status. Economic status-mortality association in males 
older than the average life expectancy was attenuated but not eliminated. 
However, there is no significant relationship between economic status and 
mortality for females above the average life expectancy.

